bioghist.head: Biographical Sketch
bioghist.p: The Lubbock Chamber of Commerce had its beginning in 1913 when it replaced the Lubbock Commercial Club. Its sole purpose is to promote the growth of the city of Lubbock, Texas, becoming actively involved through the business and commercial industries of the local area. Publicizing Lubbock to attract new businesses and industries was the general idea. The Chamber has influenced all aspects of Lubbock life from education and agriculture to sports and recreation. It was instrumental in publicizing Lubbock as a site for Texas Tech University, the Lubbock Army Air Field, the Lubbock Municipal Airport, and the Lubbock State School. Because of the many different areas that the Chamber could become involved in, separate divisions were created to handle each area effectively. For example, the Agriculture Committee was created to handle all aspects of agriculture and ranching. The Aviation Committee was formed to deal with the airline business.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Two different inventories were printed to help the researcher locate items easily.
The Inventory By Box arranges the files according to each box number and is as follows:

list.item: Government Affairs, Veterans Administrations, and Armed Services, 1917-1981 (Boxes 202-228)

scopecontent.p: The Inventory By Folder lists all the folders within a box in alphabetical order.

The Chamber records include everything from correspondence, financial material, photographs, oral histories, and printed materials. Items transferred include books, periodicals, and oral histories. Most of the collection is in good condition except for a few items which are deteriorating due to old age or water damage. If handled with care, the researcher can still utilize the collection to his advantage.

arrangement.head: Organization
arrangement.p: This collection of office files was created by the Chamber between 1919-1991 and is subdivided into committees and special topics such as the Agriculture Committee and the Maid of Cotton. It is not stored physically in alphabetical order.
